d slums, has become a rallying cry for millennial activists locked out of housing markets and unable to pay high rents.Holleran provides a detailed account of YIMBY activists campaigning for construction, new zoning rules, better public transit, and even candidates for local and state office. YIMBY groups draw together an unlikely coalition, from developers and real estate agents to environmentalists, and Holleran looks at the increasingly contentious battles between market-driven pragmatists and rent-control idealists. Arguing that advocates for more housing must carefully weigh their demands for supply with the continuing damage of gentrification, he shows that these individuals see high-density urbanism and walkable urban spaces as progressive statements about the kind of society they would like to create.Chronicling a major shift in housing activism during the past twenty years, Yes to the City considers how one movement has reframed conversations about urban growth.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aCity planning. 0aGeneration Y. 0aHousing policy. 0aHousing. 0aLand use, Urban. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh  aActivism.  aAffordability of housing in the United Kingdom.  aAffordable housing.  aBay Area Council.  aBetterment.  aBig government.  aBillboard.  aBuy-In.  aCentral business district.  aCity Of.  aCity manager.  aCommercial area.  aCommercial district.  aCommuter town.  aCosmopolitanism.  aCreative City.  aCreative city.  aCulture industry.  aDecentralization.  aElite Status.  aEnterprise journalism.  aFair Housing Act.  aFixer-upper.  aFree market.  aFreedomWorks.  aGentrification.  aGilded Age.  aGlobal city.  aGreat Leap Forward.  aGreat Society.  aHeart of the City (Kaliningrad).  aHeart of the City (development).  